SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(88)90042-5
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304407688900425
AB  - The ontological basis for causality testing must be some empirically interpretable system leading one to specify a logically valid a priori law that can be shown to exist. Such paradigms as conventional, linear and non-linear models, be they structural or time series, tend to embody contradictory assumptions that, unfortunately, make causal interpretability problematic. The paper demonstrates how these difficulties can be avoided using a stochastic-coefficient approach. The final part of this article is devoted to a discussion of probabilistic logic as a valid tool for scientific analysis and interpretation of causal relationships.
ER  - 

